article.description: Tina Thompson scored a career-high 31 points and Sheryl Swoopes added 17 as the Comets shot a season-best 57 percent to defeat the Portland Fire 71-58.
article.headline: Thompson's career-high 31 too much for Fire
article.linkText: Thompson and Swoopes rough up Fire
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes was a little grumpy, because she was on her way to an impromptu doctor's appointment to get stitches for a cut over her left eye. Yet she forced a smile after the Houston Comets' terrific shooting performance Sunday. Tina Thompson scored a career-high 31 points and Swoopes added 17 as the Comets shot a season-best 57 percent to defeat the Portland Fire 71-58. "I think we've kind of all been waiting, not only for Tina to have a good game, but for us to have a good game offensively,'' said Swoopes, who was hit by teammate Tiffani Johnson's elbow in the first half. Houston (9-3) won for the seventh time in eight games despite committing 21 turnovers. The Comets also used strong backcourt pressure to go on an 11-0 second-half run to take control. Swoopes had three steals and two layups during the run. "I don't think that we ever thought that we were in trouble,'' Thompson said. "We're taking a risk, when you run the fast break and you're running the ball a lot. You're going to turn the ball over every now and then when you take risks like that. The fact was, we never stopped. When we turned the ball over offensively, we just tried to get it back on defense.'' Alisa Burras, LaQuanda Barksdale and DeMya Walker each had 10 points for the Fire (4-7), who lost their second straight after winning four of five. Portland was outshot 69-44 percent in the second half. "Movement in our offense is a real problem,'' Fire coach Linda Hargrove said. "We aren't shifting the ball. People are standing.'' Houston trailed 35-33 when Thompson made a 3-pointer, followed by Johnson's layup and free throw. Thompson capped the run with a free throw to make it 44-35 with 11:40 to go, and the lead never dipped below seven again. A layup by Swoopes pushed it to 60-45 with 4½ minutes to go. The Comets had been averaging just below 41 percent from the field, 12th in the 16-team league. Their previous best shooting performance had been 53 percent on June 11 vs. Charlotte. Swoopes was bloodied when Johnson came down on her with an elbow while both players went for a rebound. Swoopes returned a few minutes later and made a turnaround jumper as the Comets got within 28-27 at the half. "It's not cute,'' Swoopes said of the bandaged cut. "When I went back out in the second half, I felt fine. I just felt like I wanted to do something to try to get (Portland) out of the game and get my teammates fired up.'' Swoopes, the leading vote-getter for the July 15 All-Star Game in Washington, is averaging 17.8 points over her last six games. Jackie Stiles had another disappointing game, scoring six points in 14 minutes. She has been slowed by heel and wrist injuries.

Game notes
Thompson had twice scored 29 points, the last time against Portland last July 2. ... The Fire fell to 0-7 against the Comets. ... Portland's previous franchise high for an opponent's field-goal percentage was 54. ... Burras, who turned 27, was 4-of-5 from the floor and increased her league-leading field-goal percentage to .719. ... Houston reserve guard Sonja Henning is a lawyer for the Portland firm Tonkon Torp.
